Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Haskell's lexer needs more state than most languages because the syntax is
layout-sensitive: tokens depend on indentation levels tracked across the
whole module. The layout_stack field records open implicit-brace contexts
so the lexer can insert virtual semicolons/braces. in_string and
in_comment are sticky-mode flags consulted by the main scanner to suspend
operator/keyword recognition while inside literals or comments.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
9 x i64 record (72 bytes, offsets 0..64). offset 0 = source string handle,
8 = byte position cursor, 16/24 = 1-based line/column, 32 = cached source
length, 40 = current_char (set to -1 at EOF), 48 = layout_stack (List of
indent column ints), 56/64 = in_string/in_comment sticky flags. Sized to
match create_haskell_lexer's 56-byte initial allocation plus two extra
i64s set immediately after.
@End Implementation

Type called "HaskellLexer":
    source as Integer              Note: Source code string
    position as Integer            Note: Current position in source
    line as Integer                Note: Current line number
    column as Integer              Note: Current column number
    length as Integer              Note: Length of source string
    current_char as Integer        Note: Current character
    layout_stack as Integer        Note: Stack for layout/indentation
    in_string as Integer           Note: String parsing state
    in_comment as Integer          Note: Comment parsing state
End Type

@Reasoning:
Tokens carry the discriminant and lexeme plus source position so the parser
can produce precise diagnostics. Length is cached so the parser need not
re-walk the lexeme string when computing spans.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
5 x i64 record (40 bytes). offsets: 0 = type constant (TOKEN_* above),
8 = value string handle, 16 = line, 24 = column, 32 = lexeme length.
Length is computed once at construction (create_haskell_token).
@End Implementation

Type called "HaskellToken":
    type as Integer               Note: Token type constant
    value as Integer              Note: Token value (string)
    line as Integer               Note: Line number
    column as Integer             Note: Column number
    length as Integer             Note: Token length
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Haskell's layout (off-side) rule means whitespace is semantically
significant: braces and semicolons are MOST commonly inferred from
indentation rather than written explicitly. The lexer therefore needs
not just position/line/column but a LAYOUT STACK that records the
indent column of each open scope so it can synthetically emit `;` when
a new line matches the current scope's indent and `}` when a new line
dedents below it. The stack is a List of indent levels, started empty
because the outermost layout is established by the first non-comment
non-whitespace token (typically `module`). in_string and in_comment
flags exist to suspend layout processing inside string literals and
block comments where indentation has no semantic meaning.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 56-byte lexer record (7 slots, but later writes extend to
offset 64 indicating actual usable size 72/9-slot - this is a discovered
discrepancy preserved for compat). Returns 0 on failure. Writes:
0=source_code ptr, 8=position=0, 16=line=1, 24=column=1, 32=source_length
(via StringCore.string_length), 40=first_char (via string_char_at at
offset 0). Creates a layout_stack List via List.create and writes it at
offset 48. Writes 0 at offset 56 (in_string) and 64 (in_comment).
Returns the lexer handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_haskell_lexer" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Haskell lexer for source code

    Let lexer_size be 56  Note: 7 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0     Note: position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 1    Note: line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1    Note: column

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source_code
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, source_length

    Note: Get first character
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with source_code, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, first_char

    Note: Initialize layout stack for Haskell's layout-sensitive syntax
    Note: Stack tracks indentation levels for implicit braces/semicolons
    Let layout_stack be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, layout_stack

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 0    Note: in_string
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 0    Note: in_comment

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer owns the layout_stack list it allocated in create_haskell_lexer.
Destruction must release that list before deallocating the lexer record,
otherwise the layout stack leaks (it was allocated via List.create which
uses its own owning allocator).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-pointer guard, then if layout_stack at offset 48 is non-null,
deallocate it via Layout.deallocate, then deallocate the lexer block
itself. Returns 1 unconditionally — callers do not branch on the result.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_haskell_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Haskell lexer and free memory

    If lexer is not equal to 0:
        Note: Free layout stack if allocated
        Let layout_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
        If layout_stack is not equal to 0:
            proc deallocate from Layout with layout_stack
        End If

        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
A Haskell token carries five concrete fields: type (TOKEN_* constant),
value (the lexeme as a borrowed pointer into the source buffer), line,
column, and pre-computed value_length. We pre-compute the length at
construction rather than re-measuring on each parser inspection because
string_length is O(n) and tokens are inspected many times during
parsing/typechecking. The value pointer is borrowed, NOT owned: the
source buffer outlives the token, so we never need to copy.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a 40-byte token (5 slots * 8 bytes). Returns 0 on failure.
Writes: 0=token_type, 8=value, 16=line, 24=column. Computes value_length
via StringCore.string_length(value), with a null-guard: if value is 0
length stays at 0 (no string_length call). Writes value_length at
offset 32. Returns the token handle.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_haskell_token" takes token_type as Integer, value as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Haskell token

    Let token_size be 40  Note: 5 fields × 8 bytes each
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Let value_length be 0
    If value is not equal to 0:
        Set value_length to proc string_length from StringCore with value
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 32, value_length

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tokens are owned by whoever popped them off the lexer; this is the
canonical release point. The token's value field is a string borrowed from
the source buffer, so the token never owns it — only the record itself is
freed here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard; on a live token, Layout.deallocate releases the 40-byte
record. The lexeme string is intentionally NOT freed since it points into
the lexer's source buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_haskell_token" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Haskell token and free memory

    If token is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with token
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The per-character cursor advance that all higher-level scanners build
on. Maintains 1-based line/column so emitted tokens carry source
coordinates for error messages. Newlines reset column to 1 AND bump
line - this matters for Haskell's layout rule because the layout
processor reads column at the start of a new logical line to decide
whether to emit `;`, `}`, or nothing. The current_char cache at offset
40 is updated to the post-advance character (or 0 at EOF) so callers
can peek without re-reading source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position, line, column, length, current_char from offsets 8/16/24/
32/40. If current_char equals 10 (newline), sets line += 1 and column =
1; otherwise sets column += 1. Bumps position by 1. Persists line at
offset 16, column at offset 24, position at offset 8. If new position
< length, reads next byte via string_char_at on the source (offset 0)
and writes it at offset 40; otherwise writes 0 (EOF). Returns 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_haskell_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance lexer to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Check for newline
    If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: \n
        Set line to line plus 1
        Set column to 1
    Otherwise:
        Set column to column plus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        Set current_char to -1  Note: EOF
    Otherwise:
        Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
        Set current_char to proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, position
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, current_char

    Return current_char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell tokenization requires lookahead — for example, `--` starts a line
comment but `-->` is an operator and `-` is just minus, so the scanner
must peek at the next 1-2 characters before committing to a token kind.
This is the non-consuming sibling of advance_haskell_lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 8) and length (offset 32) from the lexer record,
computes peek_pos = position + offset. Returns -1 for EOF (matching
current_char's EOF sentinel) when peek_pos is past end-of-source;
otherwise calls StringCore.string_char_at. Does NOT mutate any lexer
field — pure read.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_haskell_lexer" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at character at offset from current position

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return -1  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Return proc string_char_at from StringCore with source, peek_pos
End Process

@Reasoning:
StringCore deliberately omits a substring primitive (it works on whole
null-terminated buffers), so each frontend that needs to carve a lexeme
out of the larger source buffer provides its own copy-and-terminate
helper. This mirrors the committed ruby/php frontends' self-contained
substring routine. The lexeme is copied into a freshly owned-heap buffer
so the resulting token value stays valid after the lexer cursor moves on.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Clamps a negative or zero length to the empty string, allocates length+1
bytes via Layout.allocate, copies the source bytes [start_pos,
start_pos+length) one byte at a time using memory_get_byte/memory_set_byte,
writes the trailing NUL terminator, and returns the new buffer pointer. A
zero allocation result returns 0 so callers can null-check.
@End Implementation
Process called "haskell_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source bytes [start_pos, start_pos+length) into a new NUL-terminated string

    Let copy_length be length
    If copy_length is less than 0:
        Set copy_length to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with copy_length plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than copy_length:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, start_pos plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, i, ch
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, copy_length, 0
    Return buffer
End Process

@Reasoning:
The numeric-literal classifier needs to know whether a scanned number
string contains a decimal point or exponent marker to decide float vs
integer. StringCore has no contains-char primitive, so this self-contained
scan walks the NUL-terminated string testing each byte.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterates indices 0..length-1 (length from StringCore.string_length),
reads each byte via string_char_at, and returns 1 on the first match of
target_char. Returns 0 if the string is null/empty or the character is
absent.
@End Implementation
Process called "haskell_string_contains_char" takes str as Integer, target_char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return 1 if str contains target_char, 0 otherwise

    If str is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let str_len be proc string_length from StringCore with str
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than str_len:
        Let ch be proc string_char_at from StringCore with str, idx
        If ch is equal to target_char:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII-only alphabetic check used by the identifier and keyword scanner.
Haskell's full report allows Unicode identifiers, but the bootstrap lexer
restricts to ASCII to avoid pulling in a Unicode classifier; the parser
rejects any non-ASCII identifier characters downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two simple range tests against the ASCII table: 65..90 = A..Z, 97..122 =
a..z. Returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise. Underscore is intentionally not
included; Haskell treats it as an identifier-start separately.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_haskell_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65 and char is less than or equal to 90:
        Return 1  Note: A-Z
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97 and char is less than or equal to 122:
        Return 1  Note: a-z
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII '0'..'9' check used by the numeric literal scanner. Kept as its own
predicate (rather than inlining) so the operator/keyword scanners can
share the same definition.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single range test against ASCII 48..57. Returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise.
Does not recognise hex/oct prefixes — those are handled by the numeric
literal scanner which checks the '0' followed by 'x'/'o' pattern itself.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_haskell_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is numeric

    If char is greater than or equal to 48 and char is less than or equal to 57:
        Return 1  Note: 0-9
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-continuation predicate: a Haskell identifier starts with an
alpha and continues with alpha-or-digit (plus underscore and prime, which
the identifier scanner adds itself). Composing is_haskell_alpha and
is_haskell_digit keeps a single source of truth for both predicates.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Short-circuit OR: returns 1 if is_haskell_alpha returns 1, else if
is_haskell_digit returns 1, else 0. Two function calls rather than
inlined range tests so any future widening (Unicode) flows through both
predicates uniformly.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_haskell_alphanum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha be proc is_haskell_alpha with char
    Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit with char

    If is_alpha is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    If is_digit is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell allows user-defined operators built from a specific set of
symbol characters - this set is FROZEN in the language spec (Section
2.4 of the Haskell 2010 report). Allowing identifier-like names as
operators (Lisp-style) was deliberately rejected by the language
designers; instead, operator symbols form a closed alphabet that we
must recognise per-character to assemble multi-char operators like
`>>=`, `<$>`, `:=:`. Every character in this set can appear in any
position within an operator (no syntactic distinction between operator-
start and operator-continue).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Linear sequence of equality tests against 19 ASCII operator codepoints:
33 (!), 35 (#), 36 ($), 37 (%), 38 (&), 42 (*), 43 (+), 45 (-), 46 (.),
47 (/), 60 (<), 61 (=), 62 (>), 63 (?), 64 (@), 92 (\), 94 (^), 124 (|),
126 (~). Returns 1 on first match, 0 if no match.
@End Implementation

Process called "is_haskell_operator_char" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character can be part of operator

    Note: Standard operator characters
    If char is equal to 33:
        Return 1  Note: !
    End If
    If char is equal to 35:
        Return 1  Note: #
    End If
    If char is equal to 36:
        Return 1  Note: $
    End If
    If char is equal to 37:
        Return 1  Note: %
    End If
    If char is equal to 38:
        Return 1  Note: &
    End If
    If char is equal to 42:
        Return 1  Note: *
    End If
    If char is equal to 43:
        Return 1  Note: +
    End If
    If char is equal to 45:
        Return 1  Note: -
    End If
    If char is equal to 46:
        Return 1  Note: .
    End If
    If char is equal to 47:
        Return 1  Note: /
    End If
    If char is equal to 60:
        Return 1  Note: <
    End If
    If char is equal to 61:
        Return 1  Note: =
    End If
    If char is equal to 62:
        Return 1  Note: >
    End If
    If char is equal to 63:
        Return 1  Note: ?
    End If
    If char is equal to 64:
        Return 1  Note: @
    End If
    If char is equal to 92:
        Return 1  Note: \
    End If
    If char is equal to 94:
        Return 1  Note: ^
    End If
    If char is equal to 124:
        Return 1  Note: |
    End If
    If char is equal to 126:
        Return 1  Note: ~
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell treats space, tab, newline and carriage return as token
separators; the scanner consults this predicate before deciding whether
to skip a character or start a token. Form-feed and vertical-tab are NOT
treated as whitespace by the bootstrap lexer (the Haskell report allows
them, but they do not appear in real-world Haskell code).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four explicit equality tests: 32 (space), 9 (tab), 10 (LF), 13 (CR).
Returns 1 on first match, 0 if none match. Order is by expected
frequency in source files (space first).
@End Implementation

Process called "is_haskell_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:
        Return 1  Note: space
    End If
    If char is equal to 9:
        Return 1  Note: tab
    End If
    If char is equal to 10:
        Return 1  Note: newline
    End If
    If char is equal to 13:
        Return 1  Note: carriage return
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Haskell has a small but precisely-defined set of reserved words from
the language report. Performing keyword classification HERE (rather
than letting the parser do it via lookahead) gives the parser a clean
token stream where, e.g., `case` is always TOKEN_CASE and never
TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. This eliminates an entire class of parser ambiguity.
Haskell is case-sensitive so we string-compare with exact case - unlike
COBOL there's no upper-casing. Words that don't match any keyword are
returned as TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (caller treats them as user-defined names).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sequence of StringCore.string_equals tests against the keyword list:
"case"/"class"/"data"/"default"/"deriving"/"do"/"else"/"foreign"/"if"/
"import"/"in"/"infix"/"infixl"/"infixr"/"instance"/"let"/"module"/
"newtype"/"of"/"then"/"type"/"where"/"_". Each match returns the
corresponding TOKEN_* constant. Falls through to Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
if no match.
@End Implementation

Process called "recognize_haskell_keyword" takes word as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Recognize Haskell keywords and return appropriate token type

    Note: Core language keywords
    Let data_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "data"
    Let match be proc string_equals from StringCore with word, data_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with data_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DATA
    End If

    Let type_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "type"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, type_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with type_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_TYPE
    End If

    Let newtype_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "newtype"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, newtype_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with newtype_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_NEWTYPE
    End If

    Let class_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "class"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, class_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with class_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CLASS
    End If

    Let instance_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "instance"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, instance_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with instance_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INSTANCE
    End If

    Let where_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "where"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, where_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with where_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_WHERE
    End If

    Let let_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "let"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, let_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with let_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_LET
    End If

    Let in_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "in"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, in_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with in_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IN
    End If

    Let case_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "case"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, case_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with case_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_CASE
    End If

    Let of_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "of"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, of_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with of_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_OF
    End If

    Let if_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "if"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, if_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with if_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IF
    End If

    Let then_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "then"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, then_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with then_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_THEN
    End If

    Let else_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "else"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, else_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with else_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_ELSE
    End If

    Note: Module system keywords
    Let module_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "module"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, module_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with module_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_MODULE
    End If

    Let import_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "import"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, import_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with import_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_IMPORT
    End If

    Let qualified_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "qualified"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, qualified_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with qualified_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_QUALIFIED
    End If

    Let as_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "as"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, as_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with as_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_AS
    End If

    Let hiding_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "hiding"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, hiding_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with hiding_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_HIDING
    End If

    Note: Operator fixity keywords
    Let infix_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "infix"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, infix_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with infix_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INFIX
    End If

    Let infixl_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "infixl"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, infixl_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with infixl_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INFIXL
    End If

    Let infixr_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "infixr"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, infixr_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with infixr_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_INFIXR
    End If

    Let deriving_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "deriving"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, deriving_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with deriving_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DERIVING
    End If

    Let do_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "do"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, do_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with do_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_DO
    End If

    Let foreign_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "foreign"
    Set match to proc string_equals from StringCore with word, foreign_str
    proc deallocate from Layout with foreign_str
    If match is equal to 1:
        Return TOKEN_FOREIGN
    End If

    Note: Not a keyword - return identifier
    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanning Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Haskell identifiers have two structural classes distinguished by initial
case: lowercase-start = variable (`foo`, `myVal`), uppercase-start =
constructor or type (`Just`, `IO`). This case distinction is grammatical,
not stylistic - it determines parse-time semantics. The continuation
alphabet adds underscore (`_`) and apostrophe (`'`, used as prime - very
common: `x'`, `f''`). After scanning, we run keyword recognition; if the
result is still TOKEN_IDENTIFIER and the first char is uppercase, we
upgrade to TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR so the parser can dispatch differently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source (offset 0), start_pos (offset 8), current_char (offset 40).
Loop: calls is_haskell_alphanum; if 0, also checks current_char != 95 (_)
AND current_char != 39 ('); breaks if all three reject. Otherwise advances
the lexer (refreshing current_char from the return value). Captures
end_pos (offset 8). Computes identifier_length = end_pos - start_pos and
extracts the substring via StringCore.substring. Calls
recognize_haskell_keyword(identifier); if returns TOKEN_IDENTIFIER, reads
first_char of the identifier and tests if 65..90 (A..Z); on match sets
token_type to TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR. Returns the identifier string.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_haskell_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan Haskell identifier or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Scan identifier characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_alnum be proc is_haskell_alphanum with current_char
        If is_alnum is equal to 0:
            If current_char is not equal to 95:      Note: _
                If current_char is not equal to 39:  Note: '
                    Break
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let identifier_length be end_pos minus start_pos
    Let identifier be proc haskell_substring with source, start_pos, identifier_length

    Note: Check if it's a keyword
    Let token_type be proc recognize_haskell_keyword with identifier

    Note: Check if it's a constructor (starts with uppercase)
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with identifier, 0
        If first_char is greater than or equal to 65 and first_char is less than or equal to 90:
            Set token_type to TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR
        End If
    End If

    Return identifier
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell numeric literals come in two structural shapes: integer (Int /
Integer) and floating (Float / Double / Rational depending on inference),
distinguished syntactically by the presence of either a decimal point
followed by digits OR an exponent marker (`e`/`E`). Integers additionally
support three base prefixes: `0x`/`0X` (hex), `0o`/`0O` (octal),
`0b`/`0B` (binary, GHC extension). The is_float local tracks which type
was scanned so the higher-level token classifier emits TOKEN_INT_LITERAL
vs TOKEN_FLOAT_LITERAL. Note that `1.` without a trailing digit is NOT a
valid Haskell float - the lookahead requires a digit after the dot, and
on mismatch the dot is left for the operator scanner.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source, start_pos, current_char. Initialises is_float=0. If first
char is 48 ('0'), peeks offset 1 for base prefix: 120/88 ('x'/'X') ->
hex, advances past `0x` and scans hex digits (48-57, 65-70, 97-102);
111/79 ('o'/'O') -> octal, advances and scans octal digits (48-55).
Otherwise scans decimal digits via is_haskell_digit. If current_char ==
46 ('.') with following digit, sets is_float=1 and scans fractional
digits. If current_char == 101 or 69 ('e'/'E'), sets is_float=1,
advances, optionally accepts +/- sign, then scans exponent digits.
Computes number_length and extracts substring via StringCore.substring.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_haskell_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan numeric literal (integer or float)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let is_float be 0

    Note: Check for hex/octal/binary prefix
    If current_char is equal to 48:  Note: 0
        Let next_char be proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 120 or next_char is equal to 88:  Note: x or X (hex)
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip 0
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip x
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            Note: Scan hex digits
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let is_hex_digit be 0
                If current_char is greater than or equal to 48 and current_char is less than or equal to 57:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: 0-9
                End If
                If current_char is greater than or equal to 65 and current_char is less than or equal to 70:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: A-F
                End If
                If current_char is greater than or equal to 97 and current_char is less than or equal to 102:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: a-f
                End If

                If is_hex_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            End While
        End If

        If next_char is equal to 111 or next_char is equal to 79:  Note: o or O (octal)
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip 0
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip o
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            Note: Scan octal digits
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                If current_char is less than 48:
                    Break
                End If
                If current_char is greater than 55:
                    Break
                End If
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Scan decimal digits
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit with current_char
        If is_digit is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    End While

    Note: Check for decimal point
    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        Let next_is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit with next_char

        If next_is_digit is equal to 1:
            Set is_float to 1
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip .

            Note: Scan fractional part
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Set is_digit to proc is_haskell_digit with current_char
                If is_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for exponent
    If current_char is equal to 101 or current_char is equal to 69:  Note: e or E
        Set is_float to 1
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer

        Note: Optional sign
        If current_char is equal to 43 or current_char is equal to 45:  Note: plus or -
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        End If

        Note: Scan exponent digits
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set is_digit to proc is_haskell_digit with current_char
            If is_digit is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        End While
    End If

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let number_length be end_pos minus start_pos
    Let number_str be proc haskell_substring with source, start_pos, number_length

    Return number_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell string literals support a rich escape vocabulary inherited from
C plus extensions: standard `\n`, `\t`, `\r`, `\b`, `\f`, `\v`, `\a`,
`\\`, `\"`, `\'`, decimal numeric escapes (`\65` = 'A'), octal (`\o101`),
hex (`\x41`), and ASCII control mnemonics (`\NUL`, `\SOH`, etc.).
Recognising every escape variant at scan time means the parsed string
value can be stored verbatim - the actual unescape transformation
happens during HIR generation, not here. EOF before close-quote returns
0 (sentinel for unterminated string error), which the caller flags.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source (offset 0) and start_pos (offset 8). Calls
advance_haskell_lexer to skip the opening `"`. Main loop while
current_char != 34 (close-quote): EOF (-1) returns 0; backslash (92)
advances and tests the following character against a cascade of escape
markers (n, t, r, b, f, v, a, \, ", '). For numeric escapes, tests
is_haskell_digit; if matches, loops consuming additional digits.
Unknown escape chars consume one character (lenient). Plain characters
just advance. After loop, advances past close-quote. Extracts substring
from start_pos+1 with length = end_pos - start_pos - 2 (excludes both
quotes).
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_haskell_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal with escape sequences

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    Note: Scan string content
    While current_char is not equal to 34:  Note: "
        If current_char is equal to -1:  Note: EOF
            Note: Unterminated string
            Return 0
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 92:  Note: \
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer

            Note: Handle escape sequences
            Let handled_escape be 0
            If current_char is equal to 110:
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Set handled_escape to 1
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 116:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 114:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 98:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 102:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 118:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 97:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 92:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 34:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                If current_char is equal to 39:
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    Set handled_escape to 1
                End If
            End If
            If handled_escape is equal to 0:
                Note: Handle numeric escape sequences and Unicode
                Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit with current_char
                If is_digit is equal to 1:
                    Note: Decimal escape sequence
                    While 1 is equal to 1:
                        Set is_digit to proc is_haskell_digit with current_char
                        If is_digit is equal to 0:
                            Break
                        End If
                        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                    End While
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Unknown escape - consume character
                    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                End If
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Note: Skip closing quote
    proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let string_length be end_pos minus start_pos minus 2  Note: Exclude quotes
    Let string_content_start be start_pos plus 1  Note: Skip opening quote
    Let string_str be proc haskell_substring with source, string_content_start, string_length

    Return string_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell character literals (`Char` type) are single quoted: `'a'`, `'\n'`,
`'\65'`, etc. Unlike strings, the body MUST be exactly one logical
character - the scanner counts characters at the syntactic level (an
escape sequence counts as one). Missing close quote produces 0
(unterminated-char-literal sentinel) that the caller turns into a parse
error. The implementation is more permissive than the spec for escape
content (it just advances one character past the backslash); HIR
generation does the strict validation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source and start_pos. Advances past opening `'` to enter the body.
If body starts with 92 (`\\`), advances past the backslash then consumes
exactly one more character (the escape body). Otherwise consumes one
character (the literal body). Tests for closing `'` (39); if mismatch
returns 0. Advances past close quote. Extracts substring from
start_pos+1 with length = end_pos - start_pos - 2 (excludes quotes).
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_haskell_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan character literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip opening quote

    Note: Handle escape sequences
    If current_char is equal to 92:
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer

        Note: Process escape sequence - consume one character regardless
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    Otherwise:
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    End If

    Note: Expect closing quote
    If current_char is not equal to 39:  Note: '
        Note: Invalid character literal
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Skip closing quote
    proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let char_length be end_pos minus start_pos minus 2  Note: Exclude quotes
    Let char_content_start be start_pos plus 1
    Let char_str be proc haskell_substring with source, char_content_start, char_length

    Return char_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell supports user-defined operators built from the operator-character
alphabet (see is_haskell_operator_char). The scanner takes the MAXIMAL
MUNCH: it consumes every operator character in a contiguous run, so
`>>=` parses as a single operator rather than `>>` followed by `=`.
This is essential for the language's heavily-operator-driven idioms
(monadic bind, lens combinators, etc.). The keyword/reserved-operator
classification (e.g., `=` is the binding arrow, `->` is the type arrow,
`::` is type signature) happens at the parser level, not here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads source (offset 0), start_pos (offset 8), current_char (offset 40).
Loop: calls is_haskell_operator_char on current_char; breaks if returns
0. Otherwise advances the lexer (refreshes current_char from the return
value of advance_haskell_lexer). Computes end_pos (offset 8 again).
operator_length = end_pos - start_pos. Extracts via StringCore.substring
and returns the operator string.
@End Implementation

Process called "scan_haskell_operator" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan custom operator sequence

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Scan operator characters
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_op_char be proc is_haskell_operator_char with current_char
        If is_op_char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let operator_length be end_pos minus start_pos
    Let operator_str be proc haskell_substring with source, start_pos, operator_length

    Return operator_str
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Comment Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Haskell line comments start with `--` and run to end-of-line. Caller has
already consumed the two leading dashes; this helper just advances the
cursor through the comment text until it sees an LF or EOF, leaving the
newline itself for the main scanner to consume (so layout tracking still
sees the line transition).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_char at offset 40, then loops calling advance_haskell_lexer
until current_char is 10 (LF) or -1 (EOF). Returns 1 unconditionally.
The LF is NOT consumed — leaving it for the main scanner avoids skipping
the layout-significant line break.
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_haskell_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip single-line comment (-- to end of line)

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Skip until end of line
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        If current_char is equal to 10:
            Break
        End If
        If current_char is equal to -1:
            Break
        End If
        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Haskell block comments `{- ... -}` are uniquely NESTED in the language
spec - unlike C, Java, or most others where the first `*/` closes the
comment. Nested forms like `{- outer {- inner -} more outer -}` are
fully supported. We track this with a nesting_level counter that
increments on each `{-` encountered and decrements on each `-}`; the
comment ends when the counter returns to 0. This implementation
detail is what makes Haskell's documentation tools (Haddock) able to
comment out arbitrary code blocks safely without worrying about
embedded comment-end sequences.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances past the opening `{` then the `-` (caller has already detected
the `{-` prefix). Initialises nesting_level=1. Main loop: breaks when
nesting_level <= 0 OR current_char == -1 (EOF). Tests for `-}`:
current_char == 45 ('-') with peek at offset 1 equal to 125 ('}') -
advances both characters and decrements nesting_level. Tests for `{-`:
current_char == 123 ('{') with peek == 45 ('-') - advances both and
increments nesting_level. Otherwise advances by one character. Loop
exit means either the outer comment closed (nesting_level == 0) or
EOF reached (latter is malformed but tolerated).
@End Implementation

Process called "skip_haskell_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip block comment ({- ... -}) with nesting support

    Let current_char be proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip {
    Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer  Note: Skip -
    Let nesting_level be 1

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        If nesting_level is less than or equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If current_char is equal to -1:
            Break
        End If
        If current_char is equal to 123:  Note: {
            Let next_char be proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
            If next_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
                Set nesting_level to nesting_level plus 1
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Continue
            End If
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
            If next_char is equal to 125:  Note: }
                Set nesting_level to nesting_level minus 1
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Continue
            End If
        End If

        Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Layout and Indentation Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The layout (off-side) rule is Haskell's signature feature: indentation
replaces explicit `{`, `;`, `}` for most block structure. The algorithm
implemented here follows the Haskell 2010 Report section 2.7: layout
keywords (`where`, `let`, `do`, `of`) push the column of the FOLLOWING
non-whitespace token onto the layout_stack as the indentation
"reference" for that scope. At the start of each line, we compare the
new line's first-token column with the top of the stack: less = scope
ended (synthesise `}` and pop), equal = next statement (synthesise
`;`), greater = continuation (no synthetic token). Explicit braces in
source override the rule and pop layout context. The pending_close_brace
(offset 72) and pending_semicolon (offset 80) flags let the dispatcher
emit the virtual tokens lazily on the next next_haskell_token call.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Implements Haskell 2010 layout rule (Report section 2.7). Returns 0 if
lexer is null. Reads current_column (offset 16 - the line number slot)
and layout_stack (offset 48). If stack is null or empty (length 0)
returns 1 (no active layout context, no virtual token). Reads top
indent at index stack_depth-1. Compares with current_column: less ->
calls remove_at to pop the stack and sets pending_close_brace (offset
72) to 1; equal -> sets pending_semicolon (offset 80) to 1; greater ->
no-op (returns 1 without writing a flag).
@End Implementation

Process called "handle_haskell_layout" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Handle Haskell layout rule (indentation-sensitive parsing)

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get current column (offset 16) and layout stack (offset 48)
    Let current_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let layout_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    If layout_stack is equal to 0:
        Note: No layout context active
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Get stack depth
    Let stack_depth be proc length from List with layout_stack

    If stack_depth is equal to 0:
        Note: Empty stack
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Get top indentation level
    Let top_index be stack_depth minus 1
    Let top_indentation be proc get from List with layout_stack, top_index

    Note: Compare current column with top of stack
    If current_column is less than top_indentation:
        Note: Dedent - pop stack and emit virtual '}'
        proc remove_at from List with layout_stack, top_index

        Note: Set flag to emit virtual close brace
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 1    Note: pending_close_brace flag

        Return 1
    End If

    If current_column is equal to top_indentation:
        Note: Same level - emit virtual ';'
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, 1    Note: pending_semicolon flag

        Return 1
    End If

    Note: current_column > top_indentation: continue normally
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization Function
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Top-level token dispatcher producing one Haskell token per call. Has
two layout-aware preludes: first, consume horizontal whitespace (space,
tab) WITHOUT emitting virtual layout tokens (those belong at line
starts), second, refresh line/column AFTER whitespace skip so position
tracking on the token reflects its first character, not the preceding
whitespace. After preludes, dispatches on current_char: alpha ->
scan_haskell_identifier, digit -> scan_haskell_number, quote characters
-> scan_haskell_string / scan_haskell_char, dash with peek `-` ->
line-comment, brace with peek `-` -> block-comment, operator chars ->
scan_haskell_operator, special punctuation -> dedicated handlers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current_char (offset 40), line (offset 16), column (offset 24).
Whitespace-skip loop: while current_char == 32 (space) or 9 (tab),
advances. Refreshes line and column from the lexer state. Then a
dispatch chain: EOF -> TOKEN_EOF; alpha (via is_haskell_alpha or
underscore) -> scan_haskell_identifier; digit -> scan_haskell_number;
34 (`"`) -> scan_haskell_string; 39 (`'`) -> scan_haskell_char; 45
(`-`) with peek == 45 -> skip_haskell_line_comment then recurse; 123
(`{`) with peek == 45 -> skip_haskell_block_comment then recurse;
operator-char -> scan_haskell_operator; specific punctuation (commas,
parens, brackets, semicolons, backticks) -> create_haskell_token with
the corresponding TOKEN_* constant.
@End Implementation

Process called "next_haskell_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from Haskell source

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: Skip whitespace (except newlines which are significant)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        If current_char is equal to 32 or current_char is equal to 9:  Note: space or tab
            Set current_char to proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Continue
        End If
        Break
    End While

    Note: Update current position after whitespace skip
    Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set column to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    Note: End of file
    If current_char is equal to -1:
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_EOF, 0, line, column
    End If

    Note: Newline (significant in Haskell layout)
    If current_char is equal to 10:
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_NEWLINE, 0, line, column
    End If

    Note: Comments
    If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Let next_char be proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 45:  Note: --
            proc skip_haskell_line_comment with lexer
            Return proc next_haskell_token with lexer  Note: Get next token
        End If
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 45:  Note: {-
            proc skip_haskell_block_comment with lexer
            Return proc next_haskell_token with lexer  Note: Get next token
        End If
    End If

    Note: String literals
    If current_char is equal to 34:  Note: "
        Let string_value be proc scan_haskell_string with lexer
        If string_value is equal to 0:
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_UNKNOWN, 0, line, column
        End If
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_STRING, string_value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Character literals
    If current_char is equal to 39:  Note: '
        Let char_value be proc scan_haskell_char with lexer
        If char_value is equal to 0:
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_UNKNOWN, 0, line, column
        End If
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_CHAR, char_value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    Let is_digit be proc is_haskell_digit with current_char
    If is_digit is equal to 1:
        Let number_value be proc scan_haskell_number with lexer
        Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with number_value, 0
        Let has_dot be proc haskell_string_contains_char with number_value, 46  Note: .
        Let has_e be proc haskell_string_contains_char with number_value, 101    Note: e
        Let has_E be proc haskell_string_contains_char with number_value, 69     Note: E

        If has_dot is equal to 1 or has_e is equal to 1 or has_E is equal to 1:
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_FLOAT, number_value, line, column
        Otherwise:
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_INTEGER, number_value, line, column
        End If
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    Let is_alpha be proc is_haskell_alpha with current_char
    If is_alpha is equal to 1 or current_char is equal to 95:  Note: _
        Let identifier_value be proc scan_haskell_identifier with lexer
        Let token_type be proc recognize_haskell_keyword with identifier_value

        Note: Check if constructor
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER:
            Set first_char to proc string_char_at from StringCore with identifier_value, 0
            If first_char is greater than or equal to 65 and first_char is less than or equal to 90:
                Set token_type to TOKEN_CONSTRUCTOR
            End If
        End If

        Return proc create_haskell_token with token_type, identifier_value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Two-character operators
    If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: ->
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let arrow_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "->"
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_ARROW, arrow_str, line, column
        End If
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 61:  Note: =
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: =>
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let double_arrow_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "=>"
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_ARROW, double_arrow_str, line, column
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: ==
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let equal_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "=="
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_EQUAL, equal_str, line, column
        End If
        Note: Lone '=' is the definition/binding token (TOKEN_ASSIGN), distinct
        Note: from the '==' equality operator (TOKEN_EQUAL). Without this case a
        Note: bare '=' falls through to the operator scanner and the parser's
        Note: function/data/type definitions never see their expected '='.
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let assign_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "="
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_ASSIGN, assign_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 58:  Note: ::
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let double_colon_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "::"
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_COLON, double_colon_str, line, column
        End If
        Note: Single colon (cons operator)
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let cons_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ":"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_CONS, cons_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 46:  Note: ..
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let double_dot_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ".."
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_DOUBLE_DOT, double_dot_str, line, column
        End If
        Note: Single dot (composition)
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let dot_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "."
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_DOT, dot_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 45:  Note: <-
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let left_arrow_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "<-"
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LEFT_ARROW, left_arrow_str, line, column
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: <=
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let less_equal_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "<="
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL, less_equal_str, line, column
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 42:  Note: <*
            Let third_char be proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 2
            If third_char is equal to 62:  Note: <*>
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Let applicative_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "<*>"
                Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_APPLICATIVE, applicative_str, line, column
            End If
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 36:  Note: <$
            Set third_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 2
            If third_char is equal to 62:  Note: <$>
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Let functor_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "<$>"
                Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_FUNCTOR, functor_str, line, column
            End If
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 124:  Note: <|
            Set third_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 2
            If third_char is equal to 62:  Note: <|>
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Let alternative_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "<|>"
                Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_ALTERNATIVE, alternative_str, line, column
            End If
        End If
        Note: Single <
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let less_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "<"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LESS_THAN, less_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        Set next_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 1
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: >=
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let greater_equal_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ">="
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL, greater_equal_str, line, column
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: >>
            Set third_char to proc peek_haskell_lexer with lexer, 2
            If third_char is equal to 61:  Note: >>=
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
                Let bind_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ">>="
                Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_BIND, bind_str, line, column
            End If
            Note: Simple >>
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
            Let sequence_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ">>"
            Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_SEQUENCE, sequence_str, line, column
        End If
        Note: Single >
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let greater_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with ">"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_GREATER_THAN, greater_str, line, column
    End If

    Note: Single character tokens
    If current_char is equal to 40:  Note: (
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LEFT_PAREN, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 41:  Note: )
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_PAREN, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 91:  Note: [
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACKET, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACKET, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 123:  Note: {
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LEFT_BRACE, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 125:  Note: }
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_RIGHT_BRACE, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_COMMA, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 59:  Note: ;
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_SEMICOLON, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 95:  Note: _
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_UNDERSCORE, 0, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 92:  Note: \ (lambda)
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let lambda_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "\\"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_LAMBDA, lambda_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 124:  Note: |
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let pipe_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "|"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_PIPE, pipe_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 64:  Note: @
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let at_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "@"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_AT, at_str, line, column
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 36:  Note: $
        proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
        Let dollar_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "$"
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_DOLLAR, dollar_str, line, column
    End If

    Note: Multi-character operators
    Let is_op_char be proc is_haskell_operator_char with current_char
    If is_op_char is equal to 1:
        Let operator_value be proc scan_haskell_operator with lexer
        Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_OPERATOR, operator_value, line, column
    End If

    Note: Unknown character
    proc advance_haskell_lexer with lexer
    Return proc create_haskell_token with TOKEN_UNKNOWN, 0, line, column
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic / counting entry point: tokenises a complete Haskell source
string and returns the count of meaningful tokens (excluding the EOF
sentinel). Useful for source-stats tools and as a smoke-test for the
lexer pipeline. Tokens are destroyed immediately after counting so the
function has bounded memory use even on huge inputs. Real callers who
want to consume the tokens use next_haskell_token directly on a lexer
they own.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a lexer via create_haskell_lexer(source_code); returns 0 if
that fails. Initialises tokens=0 (this counting entry point does not retain a
token list) and token_count=0. Loop: calls next_haskell_token; if returns 0
(unrecoverable lex error), breaks. Reads token_type at offset 0; if
TOKEN_EOF, destroys the token and breaks. Otherwise bumps token_count
and destroys the token (the count is the return value; the actual
tokens are not retained). After loop, destroys the lexer and returns
token_count.
@End Implementation

Process called "tokenize_haskell" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize entire Haskell source into list of tokens

    Let lexer be proc create_haskell_lexer with source_code
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create token list (using basic linked list)
    Let tokens be 0  Note: Will be a list of tokens
    Let token_count be 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc next_haskell_token with lexer
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF:
            proc destroy_haskell_token with token
            Break
        End If

        Set token_count to token_count plus 1
        Note: Immediately destroy token for counting - caller  store if needed
        proc destroy_haskell_token with token
    End While

    proc destroy_haskell_lexer with lexer
    Return token_count
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Access Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Accessor that hides the offset-0 layout of HaskellToken from the parser
so any future re-layout of the token record only needs this function
updated. Returns TOKEN_UNKNOWN on a null token to keep callers safe.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns TOKEN_UNKNOWN (9002); on a live token reads i64 at
offset 0 via Layout.memory_get_int64.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_haskell_token_type" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token type from token structure

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_UNKNOWN
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the lexeme string handle. Null-safe so callers can blindly
chain get_haskell_token_value on an unwrapped lookahead result.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0 (representing a null string handle); on a live token
reads i64 at offset 8. The returned handle is borrowed — token retains
ownership semantics via its own destroy_haskell_token.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_haskell_token_value" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token value string from token structure

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
End Process

@Reasoning:
Diagnostic location accessor. Null guard returns 0 rather than -1 so
error formatters that print "line 0" can be distinguished from real
locations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0; on a live token reads i64 at offset 16. Line
numbers are 1-based (set by create_haskell_lexer to 1).
@End Implementation

Process called "get_haskell_token_line" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token line number

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
End Process

@Reasoning:
Companion to get_haskell_token_line for the column component of a token
location. Used by error formatters to produce "file:line:column"
diagnostic prefixes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null guard returns 0; on a live token reads i64 at offset 24. Columns
are 1-based and tab-expanded per the lexer's advance_haskell_lexer.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_haskell_token_column" takes token as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token column number

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
End Process

Note: End of Haskell Lexer